<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOD AND COMMON SENSE: 'ALTERNATIVE' AGRICULTURE IS GAINING MOMENTUM IN THE 
MARKETPLACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JEAN MAYER and JEANNE GOLDBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When word got out last year that use of daminozide (trade name Alar) might 
threaten the safety of apples, consumers were shaken. If apples -- our 
unofficial national fruit, and famous for healthy eating -- couldn't be 
trusted, what was going on down on the farm? In our desire to produce larger 
and more abundant crops, were we putting ourselves and our environment at risk? 
</P>
<P>
Long before Alar, a movement was already at work. For years, momentum has been 
gathering for "alternative agriculture." This concept recognizes the need to 
find new ways to grow food economically and safely, and without further damage 
to the environment. Its strength rests on the assumption that although 
conflicts do exist, farmers, environmentalists and consumers might all find 
some common ground. 
</P>
<P>
The movement began by questioning the underpinnings of traditional agriculture. 
Take nitrates, widely used as fertilizer. For some time it had been known that 
using excess amounts to maximize crop production was causing a buildup in 
ground water, the reservoir that lies within and beneath the soil. 
</P>
<P>
It also has been shown that levels of pesticides in ground water are rising. 
Most pesticides currently in use are herbicides, which are sprayed onto the 
ground. Previously it had been thought that they were simply absorbed on the 
surface of soil particles, where they would eventually be broken down. But they 
too seeped through to the ground water. Not only were levels higher than 
expected, but the contamination had spread far from where the pesticides were 
applied. 
</P>
<P>
What makes this worrisome is that, except for oceans, ground water is the final 
sink. Once chemicals are dissolved or suspended in it, they are there to stay 
-- unless they are taken out when water is used. No one can measure the risk to 
consumers, but evidence shows that we'd be better off with fewer pesticides and 
nitrates. 
</P>
<P>
In rural America, ground water is drinking water. Thus, farmers who live in 
affected areas responded quite naturally with concern about the safety of the 
water supply used by their families. The sharp drop in the price of crops, and 
increased cost of chemicals, provided still more reason for farmers to look for 
alternative methods, if they prove cheaper. 
</P>
<P>
Farmers are in a key position to affect agricultural practices. But they are by 
no means the only group concerned about potential dangers. The limitations of 
chemical pesticides are now understood. Insects quickly develop resistance, 
rendering a particular pesticide ineffective. And government regulations make 
it expensive to develop and register new ones. If a pesticide might be useless 
after a period of, say, five years, and it costs a lot to come up with a new 
one, the outlook for manufacturers is bleak. There is incentive to diversify. 
Those factors combine with support from environmental groups to press for 
finding safer methods of raising our food. 
</P>
<P>
These alternatives will emerge from a blend of modern advances and traditional 
techniques. One objective is to identify natural methods of controlling 
agricultural pests, making use of pesticides less necessary. Part of this 
solution lies in breeding disease-resistant strains of crops. 
</P>
<P>
In most of nature, plants grow without pesticides and fertilizers, so one 
approach will be to search older varieties of commercial plants and their wild 
relatives for desirable qualities that can be bred into commercial species 
while maintaining satisfactory yields. This plan relies on traditional breeding 
methods. But the objectives are broadened to include disease resistance and 
reduced need for fertilizer, as well as yield. 
</P>
<P>
A second goal is to provide a favorable habitat for natural organisms that can 
control pests. A third is to capitalize on natural sources of fertilizers. Crop 
residues ranging from tomato plants to corn husks can be plowed back into the 
soil to enrich it. Livestock manure can be treated and used safely. And 
leguminous plants harboring nitrogen-fixing bacteria in their roots can be used 
to furnish the nitrogen that crops need. 
</P>
<P>
None of this is a job for amateurs. Researchers at the nation's land-grant 
universities, sites of much agricultural research, are hard at work. Also, more 
and more, grass roots groups and other private organizations are exploring 
economically viable alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
On the farm itself, important changes are expected. In the past, government 
programs to assist farmers have encouraged greater specialization in crop 
production. That, in turn, led to more use of pesticides. It is thought that 
these programs will now be rewritten with an eye toward developing alternative 
farming methods. It's true that, to date, concern about problems with 
traditional agriculture has outstripped progress in finding suitable 
alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
But now, however quietly, the revolution has begun. And there is every reason 
to believe it will flourish. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Taking More Vitamins Is Not the Answer for Warming Up Cold Feet 
</P>
<P>
Question: My hands and feet suffer in cold weather. I just can't keep them warm 
enough, even with good boots and mittens. A friend said she'd read that B 
complex vitamins could help. I know you tend to oppose large doses of vitamins, 
but do you think that in my case they could provide some relief? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Sorry, but there is no evidence to support this. We can only guess at 
the basis for such a claim. Cold temperatures are a form of environmental 
stress, and the widely available "stress formula" vitamins are usually mixtures 
of large doses of Vitamin C and members of the B complex vitamins. There is 
likewise no data to support the use of these supplements in coping with stress, 
either mental or physical, but perhaps they are somehow entwined with the rumor 
that B vitamins will protect you from the cold. 
</P>
<P>
A second explanation for the claim relates to the immediate physiologic effect 
of one form of niacin, called nicotinic acid. When taken in large amounts, 
nicotinic acid causes dilation of blood vessels and temporary flushing. This 
brief effect wouldn't do you much good on a trek on a cold winter's day. 
Besides, while niacin is now used in big doses in the treatment of elevated 
serum cholesterol, it has the potential for harmful side effects, and should be 
used only under a doctor's supervision. 
</P>
<P>
Q: My 14-year-old son is considerably shorter than all his friends. I try not 
to show it, but I'm concerned. I think he eats well, but I wonder if there are 
dietary steps we could take to help him grow. 
</P>
<P>
A: No, and any claims to the contrary are irresponsible. It is true that some 
children go through their growth spurts much later than others. If he's among 
that group, time will solve the problem. Remember, too, that genetics is a 
powerful predictor of height, so it's important to take into account both your 
own and your husband's stature. Short parents are less likely to have tall 
offspring. But if you are worried that your son's growth is not proceeding at a 
normal rate, and have not already done so, schedule an appointment with his 
physician to rule out any health problem that could delay growth. 
</P>
<P>
At no time is it more important to ensure that the diet provides enough 
calories and sufficient amounts of essential nutrients than when children are 
still growing. That can be achieved by consuming ample amounts of dairy 
products, meat, fish, poultry and eggs, fresh fruits and vegetables, and whole 
grain or lightly processed breads and cereals. In addition, a single 
multivitamin and mineral containing 100 percent of the RDA for each nutrient 
can provide some nutritional insurance. Supplements sold as growth promoters 
are a waste of your hard-earned cash. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Are prenatal fluoride supplements helpful to the unborn infant's teeth? 
</P>
<P>
A: No. Although there is no evidence that they are harmful, there is no data to 
show that they are of benefit, either. To begin with, any benefit that did 
occur would affect only the deciduous or "baby teeth." It is generally believed 
that it is a good idea to start fluoride supplements for the infant shortly 
after birth. But there is no evidence that caries prevention is extended by the 
use of prenatal fluoride supplements. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Does a bulging lid on a can mean that the food inside is spoiled? 
</P>
<P>
A: Not necessarily. But all the same, we urge you not to use the contents. 
</P>
<P>
There are three reasons why a lid might bulge. It could occur in response to a 
dent in the can. Or, it could be caused by a chemical reaction between the food 
and the container, resulting in the release of hydrogen gas. Pressure from the 
expansion of the gas makes the lid swell. Then there's the other possibility: 
The bulging lid may be a sign that botulism spores are multiplying and 
producing a potentially deadly toxin. 
</P>
<P>
Since it's impossible to diagnose the cause of the bulge with certainty in your 
kitchen, the only reasonable alternatives are either to return the container 
and its contents to the store where you bought it, or to discard it in such a 
way that pets and other animals cannot consume the contents. We should point 
out that the risk of botulism food poisoning from commercially canned foods is 
minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
