<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTOR RACING; 
</P>
<P>
ASCOT PARK TO OPEN FINAL YEAR WITH SPRINT CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAV GLICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The good news at the start of a new racing decade is that Ascot Park, the 
busiest weekly race track in the country, is programmed to remain open 
throughout the year. 
</P>
<P>
The bad news is that 1990 will be the last for the old track that has been 
operating near the Gardena city limits since 1957. 
</P>
<P>
Ascot will open its 33rd season the weekend of Feb. 23-24 with the Midwinter 
Sprint Car championships, featuring the nomadic World of Outlaws and their 
winged sprinters. The Outlaws lost several of their most impressive talents 
last year to the newly formed United Sprint Assn., but Ascot stuck with the 
older organization. 
</P>
<P>
After a year, the USA folded its hand, so the Outlaws will return to Ascot with 
Steve Kinser, a nine-time champion, who rejoined the Outlaws. He had been one 
of the leaders in the unsuccessful revolt. 
</P>
<P>
The California Racing Assn., which makes Ascot its headquarters for the 
wingless sprint cars, will open its final Ascot season March 17. 
</P>
<P>
As has been the case for as long as Ascot has been open, promoter Cary 
Agajanian and his staff will have nightly fares of motorcycle racing -- flat 
track, motocross and speedway -- as well as stock car, sprint car, midget and 
jalopy racing. 
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead to the day when Ascot's dirt oval will be unavailable, the CRA 
will open its season Feb. 11 with a pavement race at Mesa Marin Raceway in 
Bakersfield. Defending champion Ron Shuman of Tempe, Ariz., was the first 
entry. Once again, he will be driving the legendary Tamale Wagon for the 
Morales Racing Team, headed by Andy Morales, whose late father, Alex, started 
the team 30 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
The 1990 motor racing season will get under way locally Saturday night at 
Anaheim Stadium with the fourth annual Mickey Thompson Off-Road Championship 
Gran Prix, opening event of a 10-race stadium series. 
</P>
<P>
Main interest in the series revolves around the Grand National sports truck 
class, in which defending champion Robby Gordon has switched from Toyota to 
Ford. Gordon will be replaced on the Toyota team by Jeff Huber, who won the 
1987 title driving a Mazda. 
</P>
<P>
Another addition to the truck lineup is Roger Mears Jr., son of the 1985 
champion, who will drive a second Nissan as a teammate of his father. Young 
Mears was rookie of the year last season, driving in the Super 1600 class. 
</P>
<P>
A new course has been laid down inside the Anaheim Stadium that features seven 
turns and five jumps. Competitors in the six classes will also encounter the 
split-lane concept introduced to stadium racing at the Coliseum last June in 
which drivers can choose between an easier but longer course and a rougher, 
shorter one around the tight circuit. 
</P>
<P>
A week later, Jan. 27, motocross will be the main event at Anaheim Stadium 
where the Coors Extra Gold Super Challenge will be the curtain-raiser for the 
Camel Supercross season. 
</P>
<P>
Crowds of more than 60,000 are expected for both Anaheim events. 
</P>
<P>
INDY CARS -- A. J. Foyt and Eddie Cheever, a former Formula One driver who is 
embarking on a CART career with car owner Chip Ganassi, have been added to the 
list of drivers who will have Ilmor Chevrolet Indy V-8 engines this season. 
</P>
<P>
FORMULA ONE -- The first day of practice and qualifying for the Phoenix Grand 
Prix on March 9 will be free to the public. A Trans-Am championship race on 
March 10 has been added to the street racing schedule, with the Grand Prix on 
March 11. 
</P>
<P>
MOTOCROSS -- The G.F.I. Winter Series will continue Sunday at Los Angeles 
County Raceway in Palmdale. . . . The CRC will hold its monthly pro and amateur 
programs Sunday at Glen Helen Park in San Bernardino. 
</P>
<P>
DRAG RACING -- Weekly racing at Los Angeles County Raceway, near Palmdale, will 
start Sunday with the first of nine Firestone ET series races. 
</P>
<P>
HALL OF FAME -- Twenty inaugural members have been inducted into the 
International Motosports Hall of Fame, which will be housed in a $500,000 
Unocal Museum adjacent to the Talladega (Ala.) Speedway. The list: Buck Baker, 
Jack Brabham, Sir Malcolm Campbell, Jim Clark, Mark Donohue, Juan Manuel 
Fangio, William H. G. France, Dan Gurney, Graham Hill, Tony Hulman, Junior 
Johnson, Parnelli Jones, Sterling Moss, Barney Oldfield, Lee Petty, Glenn 
(Fireball) Roberts, Jackie Stewart, Mickey Thompson, Bobby Unser and Smokey 
Yunick. Only retired drivers were eligible, which accounts for the absence of 
A. J. Foyt, Richard Petty and Don Garlits. 
</P>
<P>
STOCK CARS -- Three-time Winston Cup champion Darrell Waltrip has been named 
driver of the decade by the Sporting News. Waltrip won NASCAR's top prize in 
1981, 1982 and 1985, and also won the Daytona 500 in 1989. . . . Dan Press, 
1989 NASCAR Southwest Tour champion from Frazier Park, collected $7,550 in 
postseason awards to bring his season money winning to a record $46,135 for the 
All-American Challenge Series. 
</P>
<P>
NECROLOGY -- Mike Leon, the oldest active driver in off-road racing and owner 
of Mike's Sky Ranch resort in Baja California, and his wife were killed in a 
traffic accident last week en route to Tijuana. Leon, who would have been 70 on 
March 1, drove in the Baja 1000 last November. Mike's Sky Ranch is a familiar 
checkpoint and overnight stop for off-road racers about 100 miles southeast of 
Ensenada. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
