<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST L.A. FIRM FINED FOR ILLEGAL DUMPING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOSH MEYER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A West Los Angeles furniture manufacturing company has been ordered to pay 
$10,000 in fines and restitution for illegally dumping hazardous materials at 
its facility overlooking Ballona Creek. 
</P>
<P>
The sentence was imposed on Don Alderson Associates Inc. last week as part of a 
plea bargain in which charges against company President Donald Alderson and two 
associates were dropped, said Deputy City Atty. Teresa Lujan. 
</P>
<P>
The company agreed to enter no-contest pleas to single counts of illegally 
disposing of hazardous waste and failing to maintain a contingency plan and 
employee training plan for dealing with hazardous materials, according to 
Lujan, who is handling the case. 
</P>
<P>
The company was accused of dumping paint, paint thinner and other debris on the 
ground along a chain-link fence at the rear of the factory at 3327 S. La 
Cienega Place, which sits on an embankment overlooking Ballona Creek. The 
company employs about 26 people at the site, where it manufactures handmade 
specialty furniture for hotels, businesses and homes, Lujan said. 
</P>
<P>
"It appeared that the illegal dumping had been going on for some time, since 
the inspectors determined . . . that the paint contamination had soaked six to 
eight inches deep into the soil," City Atty. James K. Hahn said in a statement 
announcing the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
Inspectors first issued a notice of violation during a visit Jan. 20, 1989, and 
discovered evidence of further illegal dumping in the same location two months 
later, Lujan said. 
</P>
<P>
Lujan said Tuesday she allowed the three people to be released from liability 
in the case because they had no prior record of violations and because they 
came into "reasonably good" compliance. 
</P>
<P>
The company's attorney, Aaron Rosen, said releasing the three without charges 
was fair because they had no knowledge of the laws involved and came into 
compliance as soon as they could. 
</P>
<P>
The company also was placed on two years' summary probation by Los Angeles 
Municipal Court Commissioner Joseph Spada, Lujan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
