<P>
CZECH PREMIER LEAVES PARTY IN BLOW TO COMMUNIST PRESTIGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Premier Marian Calfa resigned from the Communist Party today, thus becoming the 
first non-Communist head of government in Czechoslovakia in 41 years, the 
official CTK news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
Calfa, who announced his decision at a news conference, was the third Communist 
member of the Cabinet to quit the party in less than two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
Only seven Communists now remain in the 21-member Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
No explanation for the move was given. 
</P>
<P>
Calfa's resignation was seen as yet another blow to the prestige of the once 
all-powerful Communist Party. More than 200,000 of its 1.7 million members have 
quit the party since the former hard-line leadership was swept from power by 
massive pro-democracy demonstrations in November. 
</P>
<P>
Czechoslovakia now joins Poland and Romania as the only East Bloc countries 
with a non-Communist head of government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
