<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: BAND-AID REMOVED FROM GDANSK'S SHIPYARDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Italian television announced Wednesday that the Johnson &amp; Johnson Band-Aid 
widow, Basia (Mrs. Seward) Johnson of Princeton, N.J., has reneged on her 
promise to Lech Walesa to buy the Gdansk shipyards for a controlling $100 
million! 
</P>
<P>
Last May, Johnson became excited over this prospect while visiting Gdansk and 
signed a letter of intent. The matter was soon being played up all over the 
world that she was "the Angel of Gdansk" and the capitalist savior of Poland. 
Actual proceedings to buy the shipyard were to be completed this month. Now, 
Johnson has backed out. 
</P>
<P>
Many knowledgeable people feel this is the better part of wisdom since the 
shipyard is in such a terrible and antiquated mess and probably could not be 
brought back to a competitive level -- given the state-of-the-art shipyards 
that do exist elsewhere in the world today. 
</P>
<P>
But this is a psychological blow for Poland. I wasn't able to discover 
Johnson's official reason for her decision; her lawyers and advisers are mostly 
in Poland now. Nor what it means to her friendship with Walesa. They were 
profiled together, you may recall, in an amazing article in the New York Times 
Magazine, wherein, when Lech and Basia were rebuked for outrageous, open 
flirting with one another, the Polish labor leader said it didn't matter, that 
his wife could not read English. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps Johnson will do something else important and urgent for the homeland of 
her birth instead of buying the shipyard. She is dedicated to reviving the 
beautiful but crumbling ancient city of Krakow. In April, she'll hold a show of 
her religious art collection in Warsaw, with the exhibition designed by the 
Italian movie and opera director Franco Zeffirelli. 
</P>
<P>
IF NEW YORK is unseasonably warm, it may be that Joan Collins is in town 
co-hosting the new Joan Lunden show, "Everyday." Joan blew in from Paris and 
went right to see "Gypsy" last night, dining at Le Cirque. This evening, she'll 
turn up at the National Center for Learning Disabilities party in the Marriott 
Marquis. Here, Joan will announce that Parlux Fragrances is going to donate a 
percentage of her new perfume, Spectacular, to the national center. Joan has 
always had a soft spot for disadvantaged children. 
</P>
<P>
THE TALENTED Robert Guillaume -- so fabulous in his "Benson" reruns but now 
seen mostly in Milk of Magnesia commercials -- is in New York talking to 
director Hal Prince about appearing in a road company of "The Phantom of the 
Opera." Guillaume served a long apprenticeship in the '60s and '70s in musicals 
and has a fine voice. He studied opera. 
</P>
<P>
THE NEW much-argued-over novel by Michael Thomas is titled "Hanover Place" -- 
not "Hanover House," "Hanover Square," "Hanover Road." So, on the blackboard 
100 times -- "Hanover Place" from Warner Books. Never mind, as Gilda would say 
-- buy it; read it! 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Joan Collins: Donating perfume profits to charity. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
